Code 
baby_data |>
  filter(Name == "Allison") |>
  group_by(Gender, State) |>
  summarise(Total = sum(Count)) |>
  pivot_wider(values_from = Total, 
              values_fill = 0,
              names_from = Gender)

Code 
allison_f <- baby_data |>
  filter(Gender == "F") |>
  group_by(Year) |>
  summarise(Total = sum(Count)) 

allison_f |>
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x=Year, y=Total)) +
  geom_line()

Code 
a_lm<- allison_f |>
  lm(Total ~ Year, data=_)
tidy(a_lm)

Code 
A_data <- baby_data |>
  filter(Name %in% c("Allan", "Alan", "Allen")) |>
  group_by(Year) |>
  summarise(Total = sum(Count)) 
A_data |>
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x=Year, y=Total)) +
  geom_line()

Code 
A2_data <- baby_data |>
  filter(Name %in% c("Allan", "Alan", "Allen"), 
         Year == 2000, 
         State %in% c("CA", "PA"),
         Gender == "M") |>
  group_by(State, Name) |>
  summarise(Total = sum(Count)) |>
  pivot_wider(values_from = Total, 
              values_fill = 0,
              names_from = Name) 

A2_Prop_data <- baby_data |>
    filter(Name %in% c("Allan", "Alan", "Allen"), 
         Year == 2000, 
         State %in% c("CA", "PA"),
         Gender == "M") |>
  group_by(State, Name) |>
  summarise(Total = sum(Count)) |>
  mutate(prop = Total/sum(Total)) |>
  select(State, Name, prop) |>
  pivot_wider(values_from = prop, 
              values_fill = 0,
              names_from = Name)
  1. In CA, Alanâs are 65%, Allanâs are 14%, Allenâs are 20% of the total âAllenâ names. In PA, Alanâs are 43%, Allanâs are 11%, Allenâs are 47% of the total âAllenâ names.

```{r}
library(tidyverse)
library(broom)
baby_data <- read_csv("StateNames_a.csv")
```

```{r}
baby_data |>
  filter(Name == "Allison") |>
  group_by(Gender, State) |>
  summarise(Total = sum(Count)) |>
  pivot_wider(values_from = Total, 
              values_fill = 0,
              names_from = Gender)

```

```{r}
allison_f <- baby_data |>
  filter(Gender == "F") |>
  group_by(Year) |>
  summarise(Total = sum(Count)) 

allison_f |>
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x=Year, y=Total)) +
  geom_line()
```

```{r}
a_lm<- allison_f |>
  lm(Total ~ Year, data=_)
tidy(a_lm)


```

a_lm |>

I do not see any patterns

7.  I can conclude that it is on the rise so far from not being cool.

```{r}
A_data <- baby_data |>
  filter(Name %in% c("Allan", "Alan", "Allen")) |>
  group_by(Year) |>
  summarise(Total = sum(Count)) 
A_data |>
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x=Year, y=Total)) +
  geom_line()
```

```{r}
A2_data <- baby_data |>
  filter(Name %in% c("Allan", "Alan", "Allen"), 
         Year == 2000, 
         State %in% c("CA", "PA"),
         Gender == "M") |>
  group_by(State, Name) |>
  summarise(Total = sum(Count)) |>
  pivot_wider(values_from = Total, 
              values_fill = 0,
              names_from = Name) 

A2_Prop_data <- baby_data |>
    filter(Name %in% c("Allan", "Alan", "Allen"), 
         Year == 2000, 
         State %in% c("CA", "PA"),
         Gender == "M") |>
  group_by(State, Name) |>
  summarise(Total = sum(Count)) |>
  mutate(prop = Total/sum(Total)) |>
  select(State, Name, prop) |>
  pivot_wider(values_from = prop, 
              values_fill = 0,
              names_from = Name) 
  
  
  
```

10. In CA, Alan's are 65%, Allan's are 14%, Allen's are 20% of the total "Allen" names. In PA, Alan's are 43%, Allan's are 11%, Allen's are 47% of the total "Allen" names.
